# 🚀 First-Year to Intermediate Software Development Roadmap 2026–2027  
**Ultra-Detailed • Step-by-Step • Realistic for Indian CSE Students**  
From first-year foundations → strong intermediate full-stack developer → ready for summer 2027 internships and third-year placements (12–35+ LPA realistic target)

You are a first-year B.Tech CSE / IT student (or just finished first year) in India.  
College tier (1/2/3), location (small town/big city), background — none of it limits you if you execute consistently.

### Your Current Level (Assumed Beginner Completion)
- One language mastered well (C++ or Java strongly recommended for placements, Python acceptable if switching later)
- 150–300 easy DSA problems solved (patterns, arrays, strings, basic loops/recursion)
- Git & GitHub used actively (commits, small repositories)
- 3–6 console-based projects completed (calculator, to-do list, quiz game, tic-tac-toe, student record system, number guessing)
- Understand computer basics (RAM/ROM/CPU, stack vs heap, compilation vs interpretation)

Now it's time to become an **intermediate software developer** — someone companies actually notice in 2nd/3rd year.

### What You Will Achieve By End of Second Year (Realistic Targets)
- 550–800 DSA problems solved (heavy focus on medium, solid start on hard)
- 8–12 deployed, real-world, full-stack / frontend-heavy projects with live links
- 30–70 internship applications sent (summer 2027 possible — stipend ₹0–50k+ counts as massive win)
- Professional LinkedIn + GitHub profile that attracts recruiters
- Ability to explain core subjects (OOP, DBMS, OS, CN) clearly for 8–12 minutes each
- Confidence to clear coding rounds of mass recruiters + many product/startup companies
- CGPA ≥7.5–8.0 maintained (no backlogs)

### 2026–2027 India Placement & Internship Reality
- Medium-difficulty LeetCode-style questions dominate 70–80% of coding tests
- Deployed live projects + internship experience = biggest differentiator for 2nd/3rd year students
- Off-campus applications + startup internships often easier entry than on-campus in many colleges
- Full-stack web development (especially MERN stack) still has the highest number of fresher/intern openings
- Companies increasingly ask deep college subject questions + project internals + behavioral stories

