## 🛠️ Phase 1 – Advanced DSA + Deep Core Subjects  
**(Months 1–8 of Second Year)**

### 1. DSA – From Intermediate to Placement-Level
**Focus distribution:** 60–70% medium, 20–30% hard, 10% easy revision

**Detailed Monthly Breakdown**

**Months 1–2 – Advanced Arrays, Strings, Searching**
- Kadane variants (circular max sum, max product, min length subarray sum ≥ target)
- Sliding Window (longest substring without repeat, min window containing all chars)
- Two Pointers (3Sum/4Sum, container most water, sort colors, remove duplicates from sorted array II)
- Binary Search deep (rotated array pivot, kth smallest matrix, search 2D matrix II)
- Prefix Sum + HashMap (subarray sum = k, longest subarray with sum k)

**Months 3–4 – Linked List, Stack/Queue, Backtracking**
- Linked List advanced (reverse k-group, detect/remove cycle, add two numbers II, copy random pointer list)
- Stack (next greater/smaller both sides, stock span, largest rectangle histogram, min stack)
- Queue (LRU Cache design, sliding window maximum, first non-repeating character stream)
- Backtracking (subsets II, permutations II, combination sum II/III/IV, N-Queens, Sudoku, word search II, rat in maze variants)

**Months 5–6 – Trees, BST, Heaps**
- Binary Trees (zigzag traversal, boundary nodes, max path sum, construct from traversals, flatten tree to list)
- BST (validate, kth smallest/largest, LCA, delete node, convert sorted array to BST)
- Heaps (kth largest stream, merge k sorted lists, top k frequent, sliding window median intro)

**Months 7–8 – Graphs Intro + Greedy + DP Basics**
- Graphs (BFS/DFS grid/matrix, number of islands, flood fill, course schedule I/II, clone graph)
- Greedy (jump game I/II, activity selection, fractional knapsack, minimum platforms)
- DP 1D intro (climbing stairs, house robber, coin change, longest increasing subsequence basics)

**Quantitative Targets**
- Total: 550–800 problems
- Medium: 380–550
- Hard: 70–150
- Revise every solved problem at 7 days, 30 days, 90 days

**Top Resources (Use 2–3 only)**
- Striver SDE Sheet + takeUforward videos
- Love Babbar 450 DSA Cracker
- Aditya Verma recursion/backtracking series
- GeeksforGeeks topic-wise practice
- NeetCode 150 / Blind 75 / LeetCode Explore cards
- LeetCode company frequency tags (start Amazon/Microsoft/Google mediums)

### 2. Core Subjects – Interview-Ready Depth

**OOP**
- Inheritance vs Composition vs Aggregation
- Polymorphism deep (overloading, overriding, virtual, abstract classes)
- SOLID principles (examples in code)
- Design patterns basics (Singleton, Factory Method, Abstract Factory, Builder, Observer)

**DBMS & SQL**
- Advanced SQL: Window functions (RANK, DENSE_RANK, ROW_NUMBER, NTILE), CTE, recursive CTE
- Joins mastery (self, cross, full outer, anti-joins)
- Normalization (1NF–5NF, BCNF) + real anomaly examples
- Indexing (clustered/non-clustered, B/B+ tree, composite)
- Transactions & Concurrency (ACID, isolation levels, dirty/phantom/lost update)
- Practice 100+ problems: LeetCode Database, HackerRank, StrataScratch

**Operating Systems**
- Process vs Thread vs Multithreading
- CPU Scheduling (FCFS, SJF preemptive/non, Priority, RR, multilevel feedback)
- Deadlock (prevention, avoidance – Banker’s, detection, recovery)
- Memory (paging, TLB, segmentation, virtual memory, page replacement – LRU/FIFO/Optimal)
- Synchronization (mutex, semaphore binary/counting, monitor, classic problems)

**Computer Networks**
- OSI vs TCP/IP (detailed layer functions)
- Transport layer (TCP 3-way/4-way, congestion control – Tahoe/Reno, flow control)
- Application layer (HTTP/1.1 vs 2 vs 3, HTTPS, DNS recursive/iterative, SMTP, FTP)
- IP & Subnetting (IPv4 subnetting, CIDR, VLSM, NAT basics)
- Basics (ARP, ICMP, routing – distance vector vs link state intro)

**Best Resources**
- Gate Smashers YouTube (Hindi/English – perfect alignment with Indian syllabus)
- GeeksforGeeks complete topic series
- Jenny's Lectures CS/IT Net
- Selected chapters: Galvin (OS), Forouzan/Kurose (CN)

## 🌐 Phase 2 – Full-Stack Web Development Mastery  
**(Months 1–12 – Primary Path for Maximum Opportunities)**

### Frontend Mastery Timeline
Months 1–3  
- HTML5 semantic + accessibility + SEO basics  
- CSS3 advanced (Flexbox, Grid, custom properties, animations, transitions, dark mode, responsive breakpoints)  
- JavaScript deep (ES6–ES2025): modules, destructuring, optional chaining, nullish, async iterators, fetch + error boundaries  
- React fundamentals → hooks mastery (useState → useEffect → useContext → useReducer → custom hooks)  
- React Router v6 complete (nested routes, loaders, actions if using v6.4+)  
- Styling choice: **Tailwind CSS** (fastest in 2026–2027) or Chakra UI / shadcn/ui

Months 4–6  
- State management: Context API + useReducer (enough for 80% projects) → Redux Toolkit if needed  
- Performance: memo, useMemo, useCallback, lazy + Suspense  
- Testing basics: React Testing Library intro  

### Backend Mastery Timeline
Months 4–8  
- Node.js + Express: middleware chain, error handling, async error wrapper  
- REST API best practices (status codes, HATEOAS intro, rate limiting, versioning)  
- MongoDB + Mongoose: schemas, virtuals, middleware, aggregation pipeline (match/group/project/lookup)  
- Authentication deep: JWT + httpOnly cookies, refresh tokens, role-based access  
- Security: helmet, cors, xss/sanitization, bcrypt/argon2  

### Deployment & DevOps Basics
- Frontend → Vercel / Netlify / Cloudflare Pages  
- Backend + DB → Render / Railway / Cyclic / Fly.io / DigitalOcean App Platform  
- Environment: .env files, process.env best practices  
- CI/CD intro: GitHub Actions for auto-deploy on push  

### Must-Build Projects – Deploy All of Them!
1. Advanced Task/Project Management App  
   → User auth + roles, CRUD tasks, sub-tasks, labels, priorities, due dates calendar, drag-drop Kanban board, search/filter/sort, notifications, dark mode

2. Full-Featured Blog / Content Platform  
   → Rich text editor, drafts, categories/tags, comments + replies, likes/bookmarks, reading time, SEO meta, admin analytics dashboard

3. Mini E-commerce / Marketplace Clone  
   → Product catalog + filters + search, cart + wishlist, address management, order history, admin panel (add/edit products), Razorpay test integration

4. Real-time Collaboration / Chat App  
   → Private/group chat, typing indicators, read receipts, online/offline status, file sharing basics, Socket.io rooms

5. Personal Finance Dashboard  
   → Multi-account, income/expense tracker, budget categories, monthly/yearly charts (Chart.js / Recharts), goals, CSV/Excel export, dark mode

6. Dynamic Portfolio + CMS Backend  
   → Public showcase + private admin panel, project CRUD, blog section, contact form with EmailJS / Nodemailer, visitor analytics

7. Job Application Tracker (Meta Project)  
   → Track your own applications, status, interview dates, notes, resume versions, reminder system

8. Weather / News Aggregator Dashboard  
   → Multiple APIs (OpenWeather, NewsAPI), user preferences, responsive widgets, caching

**Pro Tip:** After each deployment → write LinkedIn post: problem solved, tech used, challenges, live link → build personal brand early.

## 🏆 Phase 3 – Internship Applications, Visibility & Final Prep  
**(Months 6–12 of Second Year)**

### 1. Internship Strategy
- Start seriously: October–November 2026 (for May–July 2027 summer)
- Platforms: Internshala, LinkedIn Jobs, Wellfound (AngelList), Cutshort, Y Combinator Jobs, startup websites (careers page), AngelList Talent
- Target: 60–100 applications → quality > quantity (tailor resume slightly)
- Types: Remote, in-office startup, unpaid (if good learning), paid stipend
- Even 2–3 months experience = massive resume boost

### 2. Resume Creation (1-Page ATS + Human Friendly)
- Sections: Contact | Education | Skills | Projects | Experience/Internships | Achievements | DSA Stats
- Quantify: "Solved 650+ DSA problems (400+ medium)" | "Built 9 deployed full-stack projects"
- Use clean LaTeX template (Overleaf) or Canva

### 3. Interview Preparation
- Mock platforms: Pramp, Interviewing.io, LeetCode Interview, friends
- Practice: Explain projects → "Why this stack?" → "Challenges?" → "Improvements?"
- Behavioral: STAR method (Situation, Task, Action, Result)

### 4. Hackathons & Extra Visibility
- Participate: MLH events, Devfolio, Hack2skill, Smart India Hackathon (SIH), local college fests
- Goal: 2–4 hackathons → build teamwork + quick delivery experience

